Sandstone Classification

Why Classify Sandstone?

  • Helps in understanding:
    • Provenance: Source of the sediments.
    • Depositional environment: Energy and conditions of sedimentation.
    • Diagenetic history: Post-depositional changes.
  • Classification considers:
    1. Relative abundance of matrix and framework grains.
    2. Composition of framework grains (quartz, feldspar, lithic fragments).

Sandstone Types

  1. Arenites (Clean Sandstones)
  • Definition: Matrix content <15%.
  • Subcategories based on framework grain composition:
    • Quartz Arenite: >90% quartz grains; mature, well-sorted.
    • Feldspathic Arenite (Arkose): >25% feldspar; indicates rapid deposition.
    • Lithic Arenite: >25% lithic fragments; often immature.
  1. Wackes (Dirty Sandstones)
  • Definition: Matrix content 15â75%.
  • Subcategories:
    • Quartz Wacke: Quartz-rich framework.
    • Feldspathic Wacke: Significant feldspar content.
    • Lithic Wacke (Graywacke): Dominated by lithic fragments; poorly sorted, often in tectonically active regions.

Mudstone and Siltstone - Matrix-dominated (matrix >75%). - Transitions into fine-grained sedimentary rocks like siltstone and shale.

Sandstone types

Source: https://www.geological-digressions.com/classification-of-sandstones/

Key Features of Classification

  • Arenites:
    • Clean, mature sandstones with minimal matrix.
    • Indicative of stable, high-energy depositional environments.
  • Wackes:
    • Matrix-rich sandstones with a âdirtyâ appearance.
    • Formed in tectonically active or low-energy environments.
  • Framework Composition:
    • Reflects source rock lithology and transport distance.

Examples of Sandstone Types

Type Framework Grains Depositional Environment
Quartz Arenite >90% Quartz Beaches, deserts, stable cratons
Feldspathic Arenite Quartz + Feldspar (>25%) Alluvial fans, arid regions
Lithic Arenite Quartz + Lithic Fragments Mountainous regions, deep marine fans
Graywacke (Lithic Wacke) Quartz + Matrix + Lithics Submarine fans, tectonic settings
